{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638514"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:55:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:55:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17717"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78206"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10431"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63613"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8521"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24492"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78206"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHair follicles undergo cyclical changes throughout life, with each follicle cycling independently through distinct growth phases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the active growth phase of the hair cycle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Kenogen","Anagen","Exogen","Telogen","Catagen"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanagen\u003C/strong\u003E phase represents the period of active hair growth, persisting for 2-6 years in scalp follicles. This phase is characterised by intense mitotic activity in follicular cells, resulting in continuous hair shaft production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other phases are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKenogen\u003C/strong\u003E describes the period when the hair follicle remains empty after losing its hair shaft and before new growth begins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExogen\u003C/strong\u003E represents the phase when the club hair detaches from the follicle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETelogen\u003C/strong\u003E constitutes a three-month dormancy period with no growth activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatagen\u003C/strong\u003E involves follicular regression and separation from its dermal papilla\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe duration of anagen phase is a key determinant of maximum achievable hair length. Disturbances in the normal cycling process can manifest as various hair growth disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The hair growth cycle consists of three distinct phases: growth (anagen), involution (catagen), and quiescence (telogen).","Hair length is determined by the duration of anagen phase, which continues for 2-6 years.","Most scalp follicles (85-90%) are actively growing in anagen phase at any time."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63613"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a